	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1" facs="EHRI-DR-19431025_01.jpg"/>
			<p>The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-351" type="subject">Jewish question</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/maps/wikipedia_52.5167_13.4.html">Germany</placeName>.</p>
			<p>During the period from spring 1940 to Spring 1943, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864"
					type="subject">Jews</term> in Germany were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject"
					>deported</term>. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">deportation</term> began
				in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3083829/szczecin.html">Stettin</placeName> in <date when="1940-02">February 1940</date> and
				is now largely completed, so that all the elderly (originally over 65, now over 70 years) came to <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-places-place-iti-29">Theresienstadt</placeName> in the <ref
					target="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/admindistricts-212">Bohemia-Moravian Protectorate</ref>, whose former population
				had been <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1173" type="subject">evacuated</term>. The city, which
				originally had 20 to 25,000 inhabitants, now contains approx. 50,000 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term>. However, because of the fact that the
				population consists only of the Old people, the passing is still very large. Young <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> have been deployed to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-488" type="subject">work</term> in various locations in the eastern areas.
				The deportation has been practiced somewhat differently in the different regions of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/maps/wikipedia_52.5167_13.4.html">Germany</placeName>.</p>
			<p>The exceptions that apply to certain areas of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-337" type="subject"
					>measures</term> against the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> under
				the legislation, with regard to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> married
				to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373" type="subject">Aryans</term>, have not been fully observed
				during the Deportations. The Jewish spouse in such a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-375" type="subject"
					>marriage</term> is usually spared only when he or she lives with the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373" type="subject">Aryan partner</term> or with any <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374" type="subject">common Children</term>, as a rule, there is no
				difference as to whether the children are minors or adults.</p>
			<p>Thus, there are several cases where Jewish men married to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373"
					type="subject">Aryan</term> women have been deported, however, there are no cases where Jewish women married to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373" type="subject">Aryan</term> men were deported. There must also have
				been cases in which the Jewish spouse has been deported after the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-375"
					type="subject">couple's</term> only son has <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1086" type="subject"
					>fallen</term> in the war, which otherwise <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-365" type="subject">in
					Jewish laws</term> justifies a privileged position. This is motivated by the fact that the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-520" type="subject">exception from deportation</term> can only be
				justified on the grounds of the spouse or children, and that this consideration no longer applies when the child does not live at
				home, cf. above, or has fallen in the war.</p>
			<p>Although <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-365" type="subject">Jewish law</term> in principle applies only
				to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term>, there are so many special provisions
				in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-581" type="subject">Practice of Mischlinge</term> (<term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374" type="subject">Half and Quarter Jews</term>) that they must be
				regarded as a special class. In addition, in all areas where the Administration‚Äôs decisions are decisive, the principle of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-329" type="subject">anti-Jewish attitude</term> must be considered. <pb
					n="2" facs="EHRI-DR-19431025_02.jpg"/> Within leading circles, there are two movements, one that wants to restrict the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-365" type="subject">Jewish laws</term> to the real <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term>, and one more radical that wants to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-349" type="subject">liberate</term> Germany from both <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> and <q><term
						ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374" type="subject">Bastards</term></q>.</p>
			<p>Which movement ultimately prevails is impossible to say, but the radical direction in recent times seems to assert itself, in
				particular, the provision introduced in 1942, whereby <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374"
					type="subject">half Jews</term> are <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-664" type="subject"
					>excluded</term> from the army, could be fatal. One has to consider, that the definition of the concept of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1147" type="subject">citizenship</term> links to the right to exercise
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1059" type="subject">civil rights</term> such as <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1086" type="subject">military service</term> and labor service. Therefore
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374" type="subject">Mischlinge</term>, who fail to serve, are <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-659" type="subject">prevented from enjoying civil rights</term>.</p>
			<p>[‚Ä¶]</p>
			<p>Despite the fact that there is no prohibition in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-365" type="subject"
					>Legislature</term> of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374" type="subject">Quarter Jews</term>
				marrying non-Jews, the <q><orgName ref="#ehri_dr_standesamt">Standes√§mter</orgName></q> refuse to marry such persons unless there is a
				special permit.</p>
			<p>The limited access of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374" type="subject">Mischlinge</term> to - in
				the case of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374" type="subject">Half Jews</term>, total exclusion from -
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-842" type="subject">higher education</term> (including vocational
				schools) may in the future have the most fateful consequences, with <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374"
					type="subject">Half Jews</term> subsequently missing the prerequisite for becoming anything but unskilled <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-902" type="subject">workers</term>.</p>
			<p><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374" type="subject">Mischlinge</term> are excluded from owning an <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-946" type="subject">inheritance farm</term>, requiring <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-627" type="subject">Aryan descent since 1800</term>. With regard to other
				land estates, there is no prohibition, but in practice, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374"
					type="subject">Mischlinge</term> will generally be <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-333"
					type="subject">forced out</term> of possession of such property, the same applies to non-Jewish spouses of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term>.</p>
			<p><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-375" type="subject">Mischlinge and non-Jewish spouses</term> have free
				access to private businesses. Another thing is that in Practice they will often be <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-585" type="subject">pushed out</term> of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-924" type="subject">Companies</term> of any significance, especially in
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-938" type="subject">armour industry</term> ‚Äì companies owned them or
				within which they play a large role will be excluded from public order.</p>
			<pb n="3" facs="EHRI-DR-19431025_03.jpg"/>
			<p>There are still <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-852" type="subject">rumours</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2950159/berlin.html">Berlin</placeName> of further <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-337" type="subject">measures taken against the Jews</term>, e.g., it
				states that a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-582" type="subject">law</term> must be drawn up, requiring
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-347" type="subject">Aryans</term> who are married to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> to divorce. After that, the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-365" type="subject">Jewish law</term> in its full extent could be put into
				effect also for the group of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> who have
				hitherto been allowed to stay because they were married to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373"
					type="subject">Aryans</term>. Furthermore, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-852" type="subject"
					>rumours</term> have been spread regarding certain measures against <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374" type="subject">half Jews</term>. In particular, it is said that <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374" type="subject">Mischlinge</term> in cities, where the housing demand
				is high due to the devastation caused by <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1083" type="subject"
					>airstrikes</term>, should be evicted from their <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-660" type="subject"
					>apartments</term>. Whether this will happen is impossible to predict. However, with some anxiety, it has been noted that the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-342" type="subject">Campaign</term> against the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-341" type="subject">Press</term> has now been intensified again. However,
				for the first time, lately, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-347" type="subject">Mischlinge</term> has
				been referred to as <q>Bastards</q>. The fact that the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-581"
					type="subject">Mischling problem</term> is to a significant degree an upper-class problem; since the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-375" type="subject">mixed marriages</term> have mainly taken place within
				the bourgeoisie, there could also be an unfortunate impact on the position of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374" type="subject">Mischlinge</term>.</p>
